>winn</i> ‘pasture, meadow’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country’. The Bedfordshire placename may derive from Old English <i>wince</i> ‘nook, corner’ + <i>feld</i>. The Suffolk placename may derive from the Old English personal name <i>Wiga</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i> (genitive <i>-inga-</i>) or Old English <i>wīg</i> ‘idol’ + <i>feld</i>. The Wiltshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wina</i> + Old English <i>feld</i>."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Japanese: written 井伊 ‘well’ and ‘that’, the name one of Japan's great daimyō families, originally based in Tōtōmi (now part of Shizuoka prefecture), later in Kōzuke (now Gunma prefecture) and Ōmi (now Shiga prefecture). Other variants of the name substitute either character with similar sounding characters such as 飯 ‘cooked rice’, 居 ‘residence’, and so forth. It was formerly Romanized as <b>Iyi</b>. — Note: In the population figure published by the US Census Bureau, the Roman number <i>II</i> (meaning ‘the second’, i.e. ‘the younger’ of the two bearers of the name) is apparently also counted as a surname <i>Ii</i>.","History: Ii Naomasa (1561–1602) was awarded lands in Kōzuke and Ōmi for his service in the civil wars that won the shōgunate (military dictatorship) for Tokugawa Ieyasu. His family built the beautiful castle of Hikone, which still stands. His descendant Ii Naosuke (1815–1860) ruled Japan for two years as Tairō (Great Elder) and played a major part in signing treaties that opened Japan to foreign trade at the end of the Tokugawa Shōgunate. He was assassinated by adherents of the anti-foreign party."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Johannes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":37,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":46,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":81,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":112,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Johannes Wingfield II was born in 1178, in Letheringham, Suffolk, England. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs. Johannes Wingfield."},"et":{"1178–":"1178–Surnud","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1198–Male":"1198–Surnud","1205–Male":"1205–Surnud","1221–1250":"1221–1250","1178–Male":"1178–Surnud","1205":"1205","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1178":"1178","1221":"1221","1198":"1198","Abt 1205":"umbes 1205","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1180":